# t/mail/poll-redelivery-idempotent.test — routing the same inbox row twice is a
# no-op (decision-018). Persisting the poll cursor in the log opens a narrow window:
# the cursor advances AFTER a batch is routed, so a crash between the two makes the
# restarted poller re-Fetch mail it already routed. route-email must absorb that —
# an inbox row already laid into a task is routed exactly once, so the re-Fetch
# creates no second task and spawns no second run. (A duplicate run is precisely the
# raw material of the self-reply loop the poll edge must never build; decision-016.)

send allow-sender   { address owner@example.test }
send set-reply-from { address kasi@decode.ee }

deliver {
    from    owner@example.test
    to      kasi@decode.ee
    subject "hello"
    body    "first contact"
}
task 1 status is awaiting-agent
task 1 turns is 1
tasks count is 1

# The poller re-Fetches the same inbox row (id 1) — same InboxID, because AddInbox
# is idempotent on Message-ID, so the re-Fetched mail carries the id it did the
# first time. route-email recognises it as already ingested and does nothing.
send route-email {
    inbox_id   1
    recipient  kasi@decode.ee
    sender     owner@example.test
    message_id "<in-1@example.test>"
}

# No second task, and the first task's run count did not tick — the re-route was
# absorbed, not acted on.
tasks count is 1
task 1 turns is 1
